<br>
Yes they are applicable.  I think, just as we expect the best from eachother and from God, HE also expects the best from us. It is a token of who and what we are, our love for HIM is expressed through our worship and service, right?  I've often been told that 'fear' in the Bible means a certain type of respect held for someone that is on a higher order than just a casual authority.  Not afraid of approaching God, but the manner in which we approach HIM should be with all the respect we have within us, love and adoration for HIM.  In a world that teaches children not to respect parents, maybe people find it difficult to know exactly what 'respect' and 'fear' mean Biblically?<br>
I've been to several different types of services, when The Holy Spirit moves and we are gathered together as God's children it IS wonderful, it IS holy.  It is the giving of all we are, all we've been given and will be given to God's praise and glory.  Yes I think it's expressed differently by different people.  And I'm sure there are things God is displeased with, but I'm not sure how to express it in words beyond the fact of the holding back of ourselves from God, holding something back because we find it valuable and place it above God, or to praise to get attention drawn to ourselves instead of HIM, type of thing.  I hope I'm making sense?  Reminds me of the widow's mite, she gave all she had, while others gave what excess they had, what they could spare.  <br>
